@node Features

@{b}Features
--------@{ub}

- Full CLI control, with file pattern matching
- Font sensitive resizable GUI (Gadtools - no Mooey here!)
- Can handle single or batch files
- Optional conversion of CR<->LF
- Selectable serial device, unit and baud rates

See the @{"history" link History} for some of the changes.

@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Requirements

@{b}Requirements
------------@{ub}

  Any Amiga with KS2 or higher. A Z88 would be nice as well :-)
  Oh, and you'll need a suitably-wired RS232 cable.

  Only tested on the following setups so far...

  A1200, 68030/882@50MHz, 34MB, OS3.1/5, standard serial port (serial.device)
  A1200, 68020/882@28MHz,  6MB, OS3.0,   ditto

  ...so @{"accurate bug reports" link Author} are welcome!

@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Installation

@{b}Installation
------------@{ub}

  Just run the supplied installer script.

  If you want to do it manually, it's pretty simple. Just copy AtoZ and its
icon into the directory of your choice, along with the documentation if you
want. You will also need reqtools.library in LIBS: but who hasn't got it?
It's included in the archive, just in case.

@{b}Don't overwrite your version if the included library is an earlier version.@{ub}

@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Serial "Serial setup"

@{b}Serial setup
------------@{ub}

  Firstly, ensure a correctly-wired RS232 cable is connected between the
two machines. It's advisable to switch off both machines before connecting
the cable, otherwise serious hardware damage could occur - with the
internal serial port at least. It is not strictly necessary to have the
cable attached to run AtoZ, but the program is pretty useless without it :-)

  My cable was made up for me, so unfortunately I can't give any wiring
details. But you should be able to find information at the Z88 Forever site:
@{b}http://www.z88forever.org.uk/@{ub}

  Next, make sure the serial settings are the same on both machines.
That is, the various options in your Amiga's serial prefs match those in
the Z88's Panel. I use the following:

  Baud:        9600
  Parity:      none
  Bits/char:   8 (unchangeable on Z88)
  Stop bits:   1 (unchangeable on Z88)
  Handshaking: RTS/CTS

  You will need a fully-wired cable for RTS/CTS handshaking - if not, use
XON/XOFF.

  Although the Z88 claims to be capable of higher baud rates than 9600, I
have had no success with data transfer at such rates. Sending files to
the Z88 at >9600 baud generally ends up with a "Poor data received" error;
receiving files usually works but I can't notice any difference in speed!
@{"Let me know" link Author} if you do...

  If any settings don't match at both ends it is likely you will experience
data corruption. It may be worth testing the reliability of the connection
with a terminal program.

@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node CLI "CLI Usage"

@{b}CLI Usage
---------@{ub}

  AtoZ has the following command template (which can be seen by supplying
the ? argument):

  A=Action,F=Files/M,S=SendTo/K,R=ReceiveTo/K,
  C=Convert/K/T,D=Device/K,U=Unit/K/N,B=Baud/K/N,
  Debug/S

/K denotes that the keyword or its abbreviation must be typed, e.g.
Files=RAM:Story.txt or R Desktop: are acceptable.

/N denotes that a number is expected.

/T denotes that a "yes" or "no" string must be supplied.

/M denotes that multiple arguments may be given.

/S denotes that a feature is enabled if the keyword is present.


@{b}Action@{ub}

  The action to perform. There are currently four supported actions
(not case sensitive):

@{b}GUI@{ub}      - Brings up AtoZ's GUI. This is the default action.
@{b}SEND@{ub}     - @{"Transmit" link Transmit} a file to the Z88. @{b}TRANSMIT@{ub} can also be used.
@{b}GET@{ub}      - @{"Receive" link Receive} one file from the Z88. @{b}RECEIVE@{ub} can also be used.
@{b}BGET@{ub}     - @{"Receive" link Receive} a batch of files from the Z88. @{b}BATCH@{ub} can also be used.


@{b}F=Files/M@{ub}

  This specifies a file or files to act on. Currently this is only used by
SEND. Multiple files and wildcards are acceptable. Make sure you include
the path, or ensure the files are in the current path.

  If you specify the SEND action but give no files to send, a file requester
will pop up.

Examples: AtoZ send DF0:Letter Work:Stuff
          AtoZ transmit f=wb3:s/startup-sequence
          AtoZ send


@{b}S=SendTo/K@{ub}

  This specifies the Z88 destination directory used when @{"transmitting" link Transmit} a
file. If the GUI is used, this directory will be placed in the @{"Dest. dir" link Transmitto}
gadget.
  Default is :RAM.0 or whatever is in the @{"preferences" link Prefs}.

Examples: AtoZ SEND Tempish:log PC0:help.txt SendTo :RAM.1/Text
          AtoZ Transmit t:tempfile s=:ram.0
          AtoZ sendto :ram.3  @{b}(uses GUI, sets @{"Dest. dir" link Transmitto} to :ram.3)@{ub}


@{b}R=ReceiveTo/K@{ub}

  This specifies the Amiga directory files will be saved to when @{"receiving" link Receive}.
If the GUI is used, this directory will be placed in the @{"To:" link Receiveto} gadget.
  Default is RAM: or whatever is in the @{"preferences" link Prefs}.

Examples: AtoZ RECEIVE ReceiveTo Desktop:Z88
          AtoZ bget receiveto Tempish:
          AtoZ R=RAM: @{b}(uses GUI, sets @{"To:" link Receiveto} to RAM:)


@{b}C=Convert/K/T@{ub}

  This controls the conversion of CR/LF characters.
  LFs in Amiga files will be sent as CRs, while CRs in Z88 files will
be received as LFs.
  Default is "no" or whatever is in the @{"preferences" link Prefs}.

@{b}***WARNING*** Be careful with this! It will very probably cause
irreversible damage to files other than plain text.@{ub}

Examples: AtoZ send Data:doc.txt c=yes
          AtoZ get convert no
          AtoZ RECEIVE r=ram: b 1200 c no


@{b}D=Device/K@{ub},@{b}U=Unit/K/N@{ub}

  These are used to select the serial driver you want to use. They also
affect the program if the GUI is used.
  Default is serial.device unit 0 or whatever is in the @{"preferences" link Prefs}.

Examples: AtoZ get r=ram: br=yes d=squirrelserial.device
          AtoZ send jsw.bas jsw.c D=completelymadeup.device u=199


@{b}B=Baud/K/N@{ub}

  With this you can set the baud rate of the serial device. Remember to
make sure the baud rates match on both machines.
  If a baud of 0 is given, the device's default is used. This, or whatever
is in the @{"preferences" link Prefs}, is the default.

Examples: AtoZ send ram:plop.bas baud 9600
          AtoZ get b=300 @{b}(for masochists only)@{ub}


@{b}Debug/S@{ub}

  This turns on some nasty output for debugging purposes. Ignore!

@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node GUI "Using the GUI"

@{b}Using the GUI
-------------@{ub}

  To use the GUI, run AtoZ from Workbench or from CLI with no arguments,
and read on. See the @{"CLI" link CLI} section for the alternative.

  If all is well, you should now be presented with the main GUI. If not,
see the @{"errors" link Errors} section for help.

@{b}***WARNING*** Do @{i}not@{ui} enable CR/LF conversion for any files other than plain
text! This will very probably cause irreversible damage to the files.@{ub}


  The interface is roughly laid out as follows:
  (well OK, use your imagination!)

 _________________________________________
|                                         |
|               @{"File list" link Filelist}                |
| +-------------------------------------+ |
| |                                     | |
| |                                     | |
| +-------------------------------------+ |
|                                         |
| @{"Add" link Filelist} @{"Edit" link Filelist} @{"Delete" link Filelist} @{"Mark all" link Filelist} @{"Unmark all" link Filelist}  |
| _______________________________________ |
|                                         |
|  @{" Send all marked " link Transmit} @{" Send highlighted " link Transmit}  |
|                                         |
|  @{" Send to: [________________________] " link Transmitto} |
| _______________________________________ |
|                                         |
|  @{"  Receive batch  " link Receive} @{"  Receive single  " link Receive}  |
|                                         |
|  @{" Receive to: [________________] " link Receiveto} @{" ? " link Receiveto}  |
| _______________________________________ |
|                                         |
| @{"Device: [_____]" link Device} @{"Unit: [__]" link Device} @{"Baud: [__]" link Device} |
|                                         |
|_________________________________________|

  Menus:

Project  / @{"About" link About}  @{"Quit" link Quit}
Options  / @{"Convert CR/LF?" link Convert}
Settings / @{"Open..." link Prefs}  @{"Save as..." link Prefs}  @{"Save as Default" link Prefs}  @{"Reset to Defaults" link Prefs}  @{"Last Saved" link Prefs}


  Click on a link to find out what does, er, what.

@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Tooltypes
@next Errors

@{b}Tooltype options
----------------@{ub}

  The tooltype options are very similar to the @{"CLI" link CLI} options.
Any omitted settings will be taken from the default prefs file, or from the
@{"internal defaults" link Prefs} if the file is not available.

  Valid tooltypes are as follows:

    DEVICE=device name
    UNIT=unit number
    BAUD=baud rate
    SENDTO=default Z88 directory to send to
    RECEIVETO=default Amiga directory to receive to
    CONVLF (enables CR/LF conversion if present)

@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node About
@toc GUI

  Displays some information about AtoZ. Basically.

@{"Back to GUI" link GUI}
@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Quit
@toc GUI

  This quits AtoZ. Any unsaved settings will be lost.

@{"Back to GUI" link GUI}
@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Convert "Convert CR/LF?"
@toc GUI

  This switch determines whether to convert between the carriage returns
used on the Z88 and the line feeds used on the Amiga. This is useful for
transferring plain text files.

@{b}***WARNING*** Do @{i}not@{ui} enable this for any other type of file!
This will very probably cause irreversible damage to files other than plain
text.@{ub}

@{"Back to GUI" link GUI}
@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Prefs Settings
@toc GUI

  The Settings menu allows you to load and save AtoZ's preferences.

@{b}Open...@{ub}           - Select a previously-saved settings file
@{b}Save as...@{ub}        - Save the current settings to a named file
@{b}Save as Default@{ub}   - Save the current settings to ENVARC:AtoZ.prefs
@{b}Reset to Defaults@{ub} - Reset the settings to the following values:
                    @{"    Device    " link Device}  serial.device
                    @{"     Unit     " link Device}  0
                    @{"     Baud     " link Device}  0 (device default)
                    @{"  Receive to  " link Receiveto}  RAM:
                    @{"  Dest. dir   " link Transmitto}  :RAM.0/
                    @{"Convert CR/LF?" link Convert}  off
@{b}Last Saved@{ub}        - Load the settings from the file they were most
                    recently saved to

  Note: the prefs file format has changed since v1.x. You'll have to save
over your old prefs files.

@{"Back to GUI" link GUI}
@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Filelist "File List"
@toc GUI

The File List
-------------

  This is a list of files to send. You can mark or unmark files by double-
clicking on them - marked files are prefixed by a » character. Its usage
is quite self-explanatory - you can add any number of files ('Add' button),
delete the currently selected file ('Delete'), change the name of the
selected file ('Edit'), and mark/unmark all the files in one go.

@{"Back to GUI" link GUI}
@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Device "Serial device"
@toc GUI

  Changing the device options via the GUI is pretty self-explanatory. Note
that the device/unit/baud validity will not be checked until transfer
actually begins.

  A baud rate of 0 will make the device's default be used.

@{"Back to GUI" link GUI}
@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Receive "Receiving files"

@{b}Receiving files
---------------@{ub}

  On the GUI there are two buttons to receive files - "Receive single" and
"Receive batch". As their names suggest, they are used to receive either single
files, or a batch of files followed by an "End batch" signal from the Z88.
You will need to send the "End batch" signal manually, using the Imp-Export
command's @{b}E)nd batch@{ub} command. Or alternatively you can close the
transfer window

  Using the CLI, files can also be received either singly or in batches,
using the @{"GET" link CLI} and @{"BGET" link CLI} actions respectively. To abort transfer
press Ctrl-C.

  AtoZ will wait for data from the Z88. On the Z88, start the Imp-Export
program and send files using the @{b}S)end file@{ub} command. When valid data is
received, it will be written to a file in the directory specified in the
@{"Receive To:" link Receiveto} gadget or the @{"ReceiveTo/K" link CLI} option.

  @{b}NOTE: Any existing files with the same names will be overwritten.@{ub}

  On the GUI, the transfer window will show how many bytes have been received.
Using the CLI, similar information will be shown. Unfortunately the protocol
gives no way of finding the size of a file until it has been fully received.

  If the transfer is aborted by a Ctrl-C signal or by closing the transfer
window, the Amiga will cease to receive the file(s) but the Z88 will continue
to transmit. Press ESC on the Z88 to stop it.

@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Receiveto "Receive to..."
@toc GUI

  These gadgets are used to select which directory on the Amiga files will
be received to. The path can be typed into the string gadget, or the
"?" button can be used to choose a directory using a file requester.

@{"Back to GUI" link GUI}
@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Transmit

@{b}Transmitting files
------------------@{ub}

  When transmitting files to the Z88, it is essential that the Z88 is set
to receive @{b}before@{ub} starting transmission. Start the Z88's Imp-Export program
and choose either the @{b}R)eceive option@{ub} (for single files) or the @{b}B)atch
receive@{ub} option (for multiple files). With single files you may specify a
path to receive the file to, or just press ENTER to use the path specified
in the @{"Send to:" link Transmitto} gadget or the @{"SendTo/K" link CLI} option..

  With the GUI, clicking the "Send all marked" button will send all the files
in the @{"file list" link Filelist} marked with a » character, from top to bottom.
The "Send highlighted" button will send the single file in the list which is
currently highlighted.

  With the CLI, the file specified in the @{"Files/M" link CLI} option will be sent.

  After all files have been sent, an end-of-batch signal will be sent.

  As you probably know, the Z88's filesystem allows a maximum of 15
characters for its filenames, i.e. 12 characters with an optional extension
of up to 3 characters, whereas the Amiga is not so limited. Therefore when
transmitting, Amiga files with names longer than 12 characters will be
truncated, unless the file has a 1, 2 or 3-character extension which will be
preserved. Also, any spaces or full stops will be changed to underscores
("_"), apart from the . used as the extension separator.

  Closing the transfer window or sending a Ctrl-C will cease transmission, but
the Z88 will continue to expect data. Press ESC on the Z88 to stop it.

@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Transmitto "Destination directory"
@toc GUI

  This gadget is used to determine whereabouts in the Z88's filesystem
files will be sent to. Simply enter a full Z88-style path in the gadget,
e.g. @{b}:RAM.1/Docs/@{ub}

  AtoZ will make sure there is a trailing slash, and give a warning if it
thinks the path is invalid. If the path is valid but does not exist, the Z88
will generate an error upon transmission.

@{"Back to GUI" link GUI}
@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Errors
@prev Tooltypes

@{b}Errors
------@{ub}

Here are some of the messages which may appear:

@{b}Bad args@{ub}                          - The @{"CLI arguments" link CLI} don't match the template.
@{b}Unknown action 'xxx'@{ub}              - See the @{"CLI" link CLI} section for valid actions.
@{b}Could not open library xxx@{ub}        - Reqtools.library and utility.library are needed for the GUI.
@{b}No prefs file@{ub}                     - The default prefs file (ENV:AtoZ.prefs) doesn't exist.
                                    @{"Default values" link Prefs} will be used.
@{b}Warning: corrupted prefs file@{ub}     - Something is wrong with the prefs file. Note that v1.x
                                    prefs files are incompatible with v2.
@{b}Invalid Z88 directory name: 'xxx'@{ub} - The program thinks the Z88 may reject this path.
@{b}No files to send!@{ub}                 - You haven't selected any files to transmit.
@{b}Error reading file 'xxx'@{ub}          - The local file 'xxx' is unreadable or non-existent.
@{b}Error writing to file 'xxx'@{ub}       - The local file 'xxx' could not be written to.
@{b}Badly-formed binary received@{ub}      - Sign of a poor connection/unmatched serial settings.
@{b}Device error: xxx@{ub}                 - A description of the error will be given, or the error
                                    code if it's too outlandish...
@{b}Error allocating file requester@{ub}   - These are all memory problems and are
@{b}Out of memory@{ub}                       unlikely to occur unless memory is
@{b}GUI creation error                  really@{ub} tight. Free some up and try again.
@{b}GUI too large for screen!@{ub}         - Either use a smaller screen font or a bigger screen.
                                    The GUI fits on a 640x256 Topaz/8 screen.

@{"Back to GUI" link GUI}
@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Problems "Known problems"

@{b}Known problems
--------------@{ub}

- Transmitting to the Z88 at a higher baud rate than 9600 may result in 
  a "Poor data received" error. This is probably a Z88 problem and I doubt
  if it can be fixed :-(

- If the Z88 reports 'Poor data received', it tends to ignore the filename
  of any files subsequently received, using the name of the last file instead.
  As far as I can tell this is a bug in the Imp-Export popdown - just quit
  and open it again.

- If you find that you can't close the transfer window, don't worry -
  transmission still reacts to CTRL-C signals when using the GUI. This
  shouldn't happen unless you're trying to send a very small file and the
  Z88 isn't responding - I'll try and fix the problem for the next release.

  If you encounter any more problems, please don't hesitate to
@{"send me a bug report" link Author}.

@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Future "To do"

@{b}To do
-----@{ub}

  AtoZ is still fairly basic. Planned improvements are:

- Allow directory trees to remain intact
- ARexx support
- Support for the PCLink II protocol

  Some other possible features:

- Implement a new protocol to allow remote browsing of directories at 
  both ends
- Pipedream conversion
- Localisation?

@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


@node Author "The Author"

@{b}The Author
----------@{ub}

  You can contact me via e-mail at joe@nergles.cjb.net for any comments,
bug reports or suggestions.

  When sending bug reports, I would like a description of the hardware you
are using, a list of any system patches running, and a detailed description
of the problem. I would also be grateful if you could test the software
from a "clean" boot, i.e. booting with no startup-sequence, and say whether
the problem still exists.

@{"Back to top" link Main}

@endnode


